title: Account was created without confirmation code
content:
Hi

I try to describe situation with the info I have at the moment. So this started when one of our workers got email about firefox account creation, email contained the 6-digit confirmation code. Worker was alerted when in a few moment another email came also saying that account was in process to be created but here is the 6-digit confirmation code. Worker also received a third email (slightly different phrasing here as it implied that account is now existing), but now it said that someone is trying to access the account and again the 6-digit confirmation code. We looked into this and yes account was created in which we quickly changed the password. We were able to reset the password by email, since account that was created was behind workers email.

Now we know that it was workers own parents that started the account creation, but how are they able to create the account without the 6-digit code? I tried to recreate this without success.

So the parents tried to create account with our workers email and they got to the phase were 6-digit code was required, but they say they never got past it (it was in workers email), still account was somehow created.

There could a be missing link and information somewhere here and the account already existed, but still they were able to start a process for new account even when email was already in use. Don't really know how this works exactly. Could there be a bug that allows account creation without 6-digit code?

I can give more info about dates and timestamps if needed by mozilla support.

I added few pictures which are in finnish, but the idea is there. So two first were about the registeration (Yritätkö rekisteröityä? = Are you trying to register?) and last one is "Kirjauduitko sinä sisään? = "Is this you that tried to sign in?". All from same IP (parents).
creator: lassi.karppinen

title: Inconsistent Firefox Instances When Started As User vs System
content:
I'm running Firefox Portable on Windows 10. There is only one executable file in one location.

When I open Firefox as a user, by clicking the icon, I get a different instance of Firefox than if the system opens Firefox [for example, if I click on a link in a different program that opens in a browser]

How do I stop this from happening? I've attached a screenshot to illustrate the differences between the two instances:

1a/1b - User instance does not have pinned tabs, while system instance does. 2a/2b - Despite being logged in to the same Firefox Account/Profile, the toolbar is ordered differently between the two instances. 3a/3b - They're both using the same installed OneTab extension, but they have different numbers of pages stored. 4a/4b - They have a discrepancy in pages and dates for stored items.

I don't seem to have a way of selecting which instance I get manually. If I had pages pinned or saved in OneTab in a System invoked instance, without being aware it is a System instance, and my laptop restarts, I can't resume that instance and recover those pages without using another program or app to invoke it. No matter how many times I open, close, restart, whatever, Firefox myself, I won't be able to get those pages or pins back.

It caused for a lot of frustration, and doubts about my sanity, before I finally realized what was happening, and now I'd very much like to know how to make it stop and operate a unified instance no matter how it is invoked.

title: YouTube suddenly does not load on Mozilla Firefox immediately after deleting one of my YouTube accounts
content: Could someone please help me with this issue? I have been using Mozilla Firefox over 15 years on Windows and it's my default browser. I have Windows 7 professional. I never had any issues with Mozilla till I just deleted one of my YouTube accounts after discovering that I have, over the years, accidentally created too many accounts. Immediately after deleting the YouTube account, the YouTube website no longer loads on Mozilla Firefox. I keep getting the same error message that is just a blank white page with a monkey in the center holding a hammer that just says "something went wrong", with no information why it does not work. Screenshot did not want to upload to this message. However, YouTube still loads and works normally on other browsers. I was able to make changes to my other YouTube account on Google Chrome and it works without any issues. I tried restarting my PC and clicking on old YouTube links saved in my Mozilla browser history that used to work prior to deleting the YouTube account, but keep getting the same error message with a monkey. I also tried clicking on hyperlinks for YouTube videos posted on my channel, but they open on the monkey error page and don't load the YouTube website, despite the videos playing normally in YouTube on Google Chrome. I'm at my wits' end. I tried searching for help on the Mozilla discussion forums, but have not found any topic even similar to my issue. Any help that anyone could provide would be greatly appreciated. I'm a music teacher and will need to post videos to YouTube for several of my students' upcoming piano contests and this issue really has me concerned. Thank you so much for your time and help!

title: Firefox destruye los SSD a nivel de hardware si ves streaming por ejemplo fútbol
content:
Firefox destruye los SSD a nivel de hardware si ves streaming por ejemplo fútbol.

Mi disco SSD se ha puesto lento de repente. Investigando descubro que ha empezado a tener errores ECC y está en fase de ir sustituyendo bloques por los de reserva por lo que morirá en breve y ya lo he cambiado por otro. Descubro que tiene un índice tremendo de escrituras que ha acortado su vida a sólo 2 años. Mirando a fondo descubro que cuando se usa Firefox para ver por ejemplo fútbol en streaming, en el caché de Firefox se graba sobre 100MB/4minutos o 1GB/40minutos u 8GB/3partidos. Este ordenador se usa diariamente para ver partidos de fútbol en streaming sobre unas 6 horas diarias por lo que se graban unos 8GB al día en la caché de Firefox. Ya he cambiado la caché de Firefox al disco D: que es un HDD para que no se vuelva a destruir el disco C: que es un SSD.

Y yo me pregunto 2 cosas ya se tenga SSD o HDD: - ¿Qué sentido tiene grabar en la caché el streaming si jamás será usado como caché ya que nunca se repiten las imágenes y/o sonido? - ¿Se puede hacer que Firefox desactive por defecto el caché de streaming en futuras versiones y más concretamente en discos SSD?

title: Context Menu - Cut and Paste Options Grayed Out, Won't Work
content:
Sometimes, when using Firefox, if I try to cut and paste something, and I use the Right-Click context menu, the "Copy" and "Paste" options will be grayed out and will not work. It doesn't happen all the time, but it happens often enough that I think it needs to be addressed.

Say for example, I'm on Facebook, and I want to copy something from someone's status to post as a comment elsewhere. Or I'm on a webpage and want to copy and paste a word so I can do a quick search for more information. About a third of the time, the Right-Click option will not allow me to do this. The word "Copy" will appear in the context menu, but it will be grayed out and will not work.

The only way I can make it work is to go to another program (like Word) and perform a cut-and-paste operation there. Then, when I return to Firefox, it will work.
